It has been recognized since the 1930 decade that atrial fibrillation and myocardial ischemia (MI) share common risk factors, as atrial fibrillation and ischemic events share the same common risk factors such as heart failure \[[@CIT0009]\]. Therefore, when we studied the incidence of atrial fibrillation in the rural area in Nigeria, we compared the risk factors. Atrial fibrillation was found to be twice as likely in men than in women. Atrial fibrillation was found to be twice as likely in those who were hypertensive or had a history of ischemic heart disease compared to those who were normotensive and did not have a history of ischemic heart disease. It was even five times as likely in those with heart failure \[[@CIT0014]\]. A recent study by the same center reported the same risk factors, apart from alcohol use, which was not an important risk factor in that study. The risk factor profile for atrial fibrillation was similar to what was reported elsewhere. Another study in a rural West African clinic reported higher risk factors in ischemic heart disease. They found a risk factor profile of diabetes (44%), hypertension (77%) and smoking (40%), but the ischemic heart disease risk factors were not reported in detail. This study showed that those with myocardial ischemia had four times the risk of atrial fibrillation compared to those without myocardial ischemia \[[@CIT0010]\].

In conclusion, myocardial ischemia and atrial fibrillation share common risk factors, which we found also true in a rural West African population. Myocardial ischemia is a common finding in a rural West African population. In ischemic heart disease, atrial fibrillation may be the presenting symptom.

