Introduction {#sec1-1}
============

Fractures of the hip are common injuries and occur mostly in elderly men. Heterotopic ossification or heterotopic bone development (HBD) is a process by which extra bone is formed in soft tissues not normally associated with bone formation. HBD is a multifactorial process that involves multiple pathophysiologic mechanisms and is driven by various inflammatory signals[@ref1] from soft-tissues such as muscle and fascia. Bone morphogenic proteins (BMPs), which are growth factors responsible for the differentiation and bone formation, are key factors stimulating heterotopic bone formation. High serum concentrations of BMPs in elderly patients are strongly correlated with the clinical incidence of HBD[@ref2][@ref3]. Because osteoporosis in the fractured pelvis often results in increased vascularity, and because BMPs facilitate angiogenesis[@ref4], BMPs may play an important role in the pathogenesis of the ossification of the soft tissues of the hip[@ref5].

Heterotopic ossification is a common post-operative complication causing disability in the elderly. The etiopathogenesis of heterotopic bone formation is not fully understood, but there are known risk factors for HBD including aging, smoking, trauma (including hip fractures), and certain medical conditions[@ref6][@ref7][@ref8]. The mechanisms underlying the association between trauma (i.e., pelvic trauma) and heterotopic ossification have received much less attention than mechanisms associated with other risk factors. Thus, the prevalence and clinical impact of pelvic heterotopic ossification after severe hip fracture remains unclear. We carried out the present study to assess the clinical impact of the level of risk factor and to examine the correlation between the occurrence of heterotopic ossification after hip fracture and age, sex, smoking, alcohol consumption, alcohol-related pathology, the patient\'s level of consciousness in the field and initial laboratory examination data, such as the results of tests of renal and hepatic functions and blood coagulation, and the level of the Injury Severity Score (ISS)[@ref9] and the Abbreviated Injury Scale (AIS)[@ref10] after hip fracture. Additionally, the current body of evidence that a surrogate of injury severity (i.e., injury severity score) predicts heterotopic bone formation in hip fracture patients is weak. Thus, this study was performed to assess the correlation among a surrogate injury severity, such as the level of risk factors, age, and initial laboratory data measured after hip fracture, and HBD.

