Introduction {#sec1-1}
============

Choledocholithiasis (CDL) is one of the most common causes of common bile duct obstruction in Korea.[@ref1][@ref2] Although endoscopic sphincterotomy (EST) is effective for the treatment of bile duct stones, stone recurrence is an important complication of EST.[@ref2][@ref3][@ref4] Many studies have reported that the rate of stone recurrence after EST ranges from 2.2% to 27.2%.[@ref5][@ref6][@ref7][@ref8] For this reason, various methods for the prevention of biliary tract stones have been introduced. As a well-known method, biliary stricture can be prevented by inserting a nasobiliary drainage tube (NBD) before or immediately after EST. EST with early tube clamping reduces the rate of sphincter stenosis.[@ref9][@ref10] However, the effect of NBD tube insertion on the prevention of biliary stricture is controversial. In addition, in some cases, the insertion of a NBD tube before EST increases the risk of complications, including bleeding and NBD tube obstructions.[@ref10][@ref11][@ref12] A Cochrane review published in 2002 showed that NBD tube insertion did not appear to be very effective in preventing post-EST biliary strictures, although it may improve the immediate control of the common bile duct.[@ref13] Based on these factors, the insertion of a routine NBD tube during endoscopic clearance of the common bile duct in patients with cholangitis following the development of CDL has not been recommended by many authors.[@ref7][@ref13][@ref14]

Some recent studies have shown that the early placement of a NBD tube after biliary stricture and endoscopic stricture dilation could achieve a reduction rate of biliary stricture without a significant post-operative complication rate.[@ref9][@ref10][@ref15] However, few studies have investigated the efficacy and safety of NBD tube placement based on the pre-EST placement of a NBD tube. We therefore performed a randomized controlled study, in which 1 week after EST we performed pre-EST placement of a NBD tube in patients with cholangitis associated with CDL. We examined whether routine placement of a NBD tube increased the incidence of postoperative complications after EST and led to the recurrence of stones after EST. To prevent stone recurrence after EST, we attempted to determine what is the minimum interval that would minimize the risk of stone recurrence. We also assessed whether routine placement of a NBD tube in patients with cholangitis after the development of CDL could prevent biliary stricture.

