Methods {#s1}
=======

Design of the study {#s1a}
-------------------

A prospective pre- and post-test study was conducted over a 2-month period in a medical and respiratory care unit in a tertiary university-affiliated hospital. Participants were selected randomly after applying the inclusion and exclusion criteria. Those who agreed to take part in the study signed the consent form. The participants and researcher agreed that if a patient became disoriented or agitated and could not continue in the music intervention, the researcher would stop the intervention but would continue monitoring the subject for behavioral changes. This was done to avoid the bias caused by the interruption in the intervention as in other studies that showed the effectiveness of music therapy \[[@R4],[@R5]\]. Participants were divided into two groups based on the musical characteristics of the songs in the playlist: the peaceful group listened to classical, soft, mellow songs and the disturbing group listened to loud, fast, active types of music. This grouping was based on the assumption that calming music might reduce stress in a certain group of patients.

Participants {#s1b}
------------

The inclusion criteria were: patients admitted in the medical and respiratory care unit and mechanical ventilated. Exclusion criteria included: patients with no history of hearing loss (according to a history of previous hospitalization), patients who were exposed to music therapy in the medical and respiratory ward, as well as patients who had a long-term coma (more than 4 hours).

Data collection and study instruments {#s1c}
-------------------------------------

Evaluation of the stress levels in the participants was carried out using the Perceived Stress Scale (PSS) \[[@R6]\]. For validity and reliability of the questionnaire, a pilot test was carried out on 20 patients in the respiratory ward with similar clinical presentation who were not included in the main study. Data collection was conducted twice in different times of the day (at 7:00 am and 6:00 pm) to eliminate bias in response to the study instruments and the same examiner conducted the process to standardize the study. Patients in both groups were asked to fill out the questionnaire at these two times of the day and the obtained score of each was compared using the Wilcoxon test (test of significance).

Procedures, intervention and statistical analysis {#s1d}
------------------------------------------------

The selected music was played on an ipod shuffle (apple, 5th generation) in each of the groups while the rest of the staff was asked to maintain their regular ward music and play what is preferred by the patient according to the ward environment. In both groups, the researcher played the same music for 3 consecutive days. Patients were also asked about their preference of the type of music they liked in the music group. The duration of exposure to the music was not reported as the researcher believed that this variable did not influence the results \[[@R7]\]. The intervention began when a patient was admitted in the medical or respiratory ward; however, if the participant had already been in the ward in previous days, the initial intervention was delayed for approximately 2 hours to allow the patient to be included in the study. This was to minimize interference with the routine interventions. Data collection instruments included two sections, one regarding the participant's demographic data and the other concerning the participants' perceived stress levels using the PSS. PSS was used based on its validity and reliability based on a previous study on this subject \[[@R6]\]. To determine the effect of the music on perceived stress, the Wilcoxon test was used to compare the post-test to baseline (control) and the mean PSS scores between the two groups, then the data was presented through tables and graphs. All analyses were performed using the statistical software SPSS 21.0, while the P-value was considered significant if less than 0.05.

