 What we do affects whom we select as friends. When parents drink during adolescence, their children select friends whose drinking is as high as or higher than their own, and their alcohol exposure increases as a result.[@b1] Similarly, when we select our friends to drink in tandem with us, our drinking increases as a result of their drinking with us. The evidence that what we do influences who we are friends with is called *social selection*. In other words, what we do influences the social environments that we occupy.[@b2] When we act in ways that increase the likelihood that we will become friends with other people, those people can influence how we behave.[@b3] Therefore, the familial nature of human behavior is not limited strictly to behavior that is transmitted through genes.

The evidence of social selection has been found using a variety of methods outside of laboratory experiments. In the following discussion, we use two studies that employ similar methods: children\'s social networks and longitudinal alcohol consumption surveys of the National Household Survey of Drug Abuse.[@b4],[@b5] Both studies demonstrate the power of social selection in predicting human outcomes. Children\'s social networks have been shown to be a valid proxy for adult social networks in predicting risky sexual behavior in both adolescence (e.g., early sexual initiation)[@b6],[@b7] and adulthood (e.g., substance use and HIV/AIDS).[@b4],[@b8]--[@b12] Because these outcomes are highly heritable,[@b8]--[@b12] we can be confident in the conclusion that the familial transmission of risk-taking behaviors persists into adulthood.

In the same way, a longitudinal population survey of alcohol abuse in four counties in the Pacific northwest found a familial relationship between adolescent's drinking and that of their adult friends, which predicted adolescent alcohol consumption levels into young adulthood.[@b5] Alcoholism is a highly heritable disorder,[@b13] and so, for us to draw a conclusion about how genetic influences on drinking differ for those children who have alcohol-exposed parents versus those whose parents abstain from alcohol, we would also need to demonstrate that genetic influences on alcohol abuse affect children in ways that are independent of that of their parents.

Family-of-origin drinking patterns often have a substantial effect on adult behavior,[@b2] but this does not mean that other factors, such as genetics, are not important. One way to isolate genetic influences (in addition to the environment) on an outcome is to compare twins to nonidentical siblings. This twin-sibling study approach (see Figure [1](#fig01){ref-type="fig"}) assumes that heritable effects of risk factors will be larger in siblings than in nonmonozygotic twins because the risk factor influences each twin, while the other sibling experiences the influence only if both the twins share that risk factor. An alternative hypothesis is that heritable familial influences will be larger in non-identical twins than in siblings, because the other twin in a pair has genes different from those already present in the first twin. If this second hypothesis is true, a twin-sibling study would produce nonmonstrous results even in the presence of substantial environmental effects, because both twins are genetically similar. Figure [2](#fig02){ref-type="fig"} illustrates differences between nonidentical versus nonmonozygotic twins, and Figure [3](#fig03){ref-type="fig"} illustrates effects attributable to genetic versus environmental processes among monozygotic versus nonmonozygotic twins.

